quran[14]{c,v,t}:
  19,12,"“O John, hold on to the Scripture firmly,” and We gave him wise judgment in his youth"
  19,13,"and tenderness from Us and purity, and he was mindful<i class=""s"">(of God) </i>,"
  19,14,"and was very kind to his parents, and he was never a disobedient coercer."
  19,15,"And peace be upon him the day he was born and the day he dies and the day he is resurrected alive."
  19,16,"And remember<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>in the Scripture Mary, when she secluded herself from her family in an eastern location."
  19,17,"And she took a cover for herself away from them, and We sent to her Our spirit, so He appeared to her as a human being in perfect shape."
  19,18,"She said, “I seek refuge from you with the All-Merciful, if you are mindful<i class=""s"">(of God) </i>.”"
  19,19,"He said, “I am only a messenger of your Lord <span class="h">to grant{1}</span>you a pure boy.”",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Warsh, Abu Amr, Ya’qub and Qaloun, in one of his narrations, read it as: “…of your Lord so that He may grant you…”</span>
  19,20,"She said, “How can I have a boy when no human being has touched me, nor have I ever been a harlot?”"
  19,21,"He said, “Thus said your Lord, ‘It is easy for Me, and We will make him a sign for humanity and a mercy from Us, and it has been a matter already decreed.’”"
  19,22,"So she carried him and secluded herself with him in a remote place."
  19,23,"Then the birth pangs compelled her to come to the trunk of the palm tree. She said, “If only I had died before this and been a thing forgotten, completely forgotten!”"
  19,24,"<span class="h">So he called her from beneath her{1}</span>: “Be not sad; your Lord has made a stream beneath you.",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Shu’ba and Roways read it as: “So the one beneath her called her:”</span>
  19,25,"And shake the trunk of the palm tree towards you—<span class="h">it{1}</span><span class=""h"">will drop ripe dates</span>upon you.”",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “…it (masculine – referring to the trunk) will drop…” All others read it as: “…it (feminine – referring to the palm tree itself) will drop...”</span>
